Here's a GitHub API example (replace YOUR_GITHUB_TOKEN):
```bash
curl -X POST \
  https://api.github.com/repos \
  -H 'Authorization: Bearer YOUR_GITHUB_TOKEN' \
  -d '{
    "name": "secure-project",
    "branch_protection_rules": [{
      "pattern": "main",
      "required_pull_request_reviews": {"dismiss_stale_reviews": true}
    }]
  }'
```
For UI setup: Create repo on GitHub > Settings > Branches > Add 'main' protection rule.

Run this script in your repository root:
```bash
#!/bin/bash
IFS=$'\n';
objects=`git verify-pack -v .git/objects/pack/pack-*.idx | grep -v chain | sort -k3nr | head`;
echo "All sizes are in kB's. The pack column is the compressed size:";
output="size,pack,SHA,location";
allObjects=`git rev-list --all --objects`;
for y in $objects; do
    size=$((`echo $y | cut -f 5 -d ' '`/1024));
    compressedSize=$((`echo $y | cut -f 6 -d ' '`/1024));
    sha=`echo $y | cut -f 1 -d ' '`;
    other=`echo "${allObjects}" | grep $sha`;
    output="${output}\n${size},${compressedSize},${other}";
done;
echo -e $output | column -t -s ', '
```

Use this structure to suppress all output while preserving error handling:
`git push origin > /dev/null 2>&1 || echo "Push failed"`

For cron jobs, here's a robust function:
```bash
quiet_git() {
    git "$@" > /dev/null 2>&1 || { echo "Command failed: git $@" >&2; exit 1; }
}
```
Use it with `quiet_git push origin`.

Create a Jenkinsfile with this structure:
```groovy
node {
  dir('repo1') {
    git url: 'REPO1_URL'
  }
  dir('repo2') {
    git url: 'REPO2_URL'
  }
  dir('repo3') {
    git url: 'REPO3_URL'
  }
}
```
Replace `REPO*_URL` with your actual repository URLs. This ensures each repo is checked out to its own subdirectory.

Here's a pipeline script using `dir` blocks to check out each repository into its subdirectory:
```groovy
node('ATLAS && Linux') {
    dir('CalibrationResults') {
        git url: 'https://github.com/AtlasBID/CalibrationResults.git'
    }
    dir('Combination') {
        git url: 'https://github.com/AtlasBID/Combination.git'
    }
    dir('CombinationBuilder') {
        git url: 'https://github.com/AtlasBID/CombinationBuilder.git'
    }
    sh('ls')
    sh('. CombinationBuilder/build.sh')
}
```

Here's a simple implementation using `exec`:
```bash
require('child_process').exec('git rev-parse HEAD', (err, stdout) => {
  console.log('Latest commit hash:', stdout.trim());
});
```
For a synchronous version, replace `exec` with `execSync` and remove the callback.

Here's the synchronous implementation:
```bash
const commitHash = require('child_process').execSync('git rev-parse HEAD').toString().trim();
console.log('Latest hash:', commitHash);
```
This will block execution until the command completes.
